{
  "texts": [
    "For part 2, if F ′ ⊮ φ, then there is a possibility model M ′ = ⟨F ′, π ′ ⟩ and y ′ ∈ M ′ such that M ′, y ′ ⊮ φ, in which case Refinability implies that there is an x ′ ⊑ ′ y ′ such that M ′, x ′ ⊩ ¬φ.",
    "Given our morphism h from F to F ′, define a valuation π on F by π(p) = h -1 [π ′ (p)].",
    "Then h -1 [π ′ (p)] ∈ P by pull back, so M = ⟨F, π⟩ is an admissible model based on F, and h is a possibility morphism from M to M ′ according to Definition 3.2.15.",
    "Finally, since h is a dense possibility morphism from F to F ′, there is an x ∈ M such that h(x) ⊑ ′ x ′, which with M, x ′ ⊩ ¬φ implies M ′, h(x) ⊮ φ, which with part 1 implies M, x ⊮ φ, so F ⊮ φ.For part 3, suppose F ⊮ φ, so there is a possibility model M = ⟨F, π⟩ andx ∈ M such that M, x ⊮ φ.",
    "Since our morphism h from F to F ′ is robust, we can choose for each p ∈ Φ a π ′ (p) ∈ P ′ such that h[π(p)] = h[S] ∩ π ′ (p)."
  ]
}